30:54.853 --> 30:56.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why is this even close?

30:56.421 --> 30:58.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANNA RAU, Montana PBS: Well,
that's the question,
actually, going forward.

30:58.990 --> 31:03.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think people are watching
it from the
outside very closely, because it
has tightened

31:03.695 --> 31:05.463 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the last month.

31:05.496 --> 31:08.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have seen it go from maybe
15 -- 12 to
15 points, and then internal
polling within

31:08.266 --> 31:13.705 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the campaigns are showing closer
maybe eight
to 10 points, maybe six to eight
points, so

31:13.738 --> 31:16.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in some of the best polls for
the Democrats.

31:16.307 --> 31:18.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let's talk
about the
candidates in this race.

31:18.676 --> 31:21.479 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Tell us just quickly the
differences between
the two of them.

31:21.512 --> 31:22.614 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ANNA RAU: OK.

31:22.647 --> 31:24.916 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, they're both outsiders,
political outsiders.

31:24.949 --> 31:29.153 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But Rob Quist is a country
bluegrass player.

31:29.187 --> 31:31.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He played with the Mission
Mountain Wood Band
back in the '70s.

31:31.256 --> 31:34.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's very popular throughout the
state for
his music, but has absolutely no
political

31:34.993 --> 31:36.828 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
experience.

31:36.861 --> 31:41.699 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And Greg Gianforte is a
millionaire from Bozeman
who made his money creating a
great business

31:41.733 --> 31:43.701 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Montana that employed over
500 people.

31:43.735 --> 31:47.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So he created all these
high-wage jobs in
the software business in
Bozeman.

31:47.705 --> 31:52.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So he has this kind of business
acumen behind
him, but, again, very little
political experience.

31:52.210 --> 31:57.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He did run for governor in
November, but lost
narrowly to Governor Bullock,
who was the

31:57.715 --> 31:59.484 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
incumbent.

31:59.517 --> 32:02.120 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think there was a
situation there where
the whole ticket went red,
except for the

32:02.153 --> 32:03.922 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
governor's race.

32:03.955 --> 32:07.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So some of those Republicans
actually crossed
when they got to Gianforte and
Bullock, and

32:07.125 --> 32:08.893 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
voted for Bullock.

32:08.927 --> 32:11.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that's been kind of a thing
here too that
Quist think he's got a shot, and
Democrats

32:11.629 --> 32:14.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
think they have a shot because
of what happened
in the governor's race.

32:14.198 --> 32:16.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it's kind of those two
candidates, very
colorful candidate.s

32:16.501 --> 32:22.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do polls and
your interviews
with voters tell you, though, is
most on voters'

32:22.273 --> 32:24.042 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
minds?

32:24.075 --> 32:28.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNA RAU: Well, early on in the
campaign,
it sounds like the two
candidates were saying

32:28.313 --> 32:33.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
public lands and regulations out
of Washington
were the big issues, because out
West we have

32:33.418 --> 32:35.954 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the extractive industries,
timber and mining.

32:35.987 --> 32:39.991 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so when it came to
Republican voters,
they were very concerned about
EPA regulation

32:40.024 --> 32:41.893 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and government overreach.

32:41.926 --> 32:45.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When it came to Democrat voters
and some Republican
voters, public lands and public
access was

32:45.797 --> 32:47.031 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a big issue.

32:47.065 --> 32:49.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Montana, we have over 25
million acres
of public land.

32:49.867 --> 32:51.602 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Also, health care.

32:51.636 --> 32:54.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the very end here, health
care has really
picked up, especially with
what's going on

32:54.472 --> 32:56.107 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in Washington, D.C.

32:56.140 --> 32:59.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Gianforte and Quist have
come out very
strongly on the health care
bill.

32:59.644 --> 33:01.980 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And there's been some
controversy about their
positions on it.

33:02.013 --> 33:05.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Quist has made that a
cornerstone of his
campaign because he had a health
care issue

33:05.650 --> 33:11.322 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in the '90s that he says
explains some of
his problems financially and is
in favor of

33:11.356 --> 33:13.257 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
maybe a single-payer program.

33:13.291 --> 33:17.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Gianforte, for his part, has
said he wouldn't
support the current repeal and
replace.

33:17.662 --> 33:20.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And just very
quick final question.

33:20.331 --> 33:22.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How much has Donald Trump,
President Trump,
come up in this campaign?

33:22.233 --> 33:24.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNA RAU: Well, JUDY WOODRUFF:
How much has
President Trump come up in this
campaign?

33:24.202 --> 33:28.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, Gianforte has said from
the very beginning,
make no mistake about this, this
is a referendum

33:28.339 --> 33:29.307 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on Donald Trump.

33:29.340 --> 33:32.310 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think that he was very popular
in Montana.

33:32.343 --> 33:36.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Quist tries to make it --
his campaign
tries to make it less about
Trump and more

33:36.280 --> 33:38.516 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about the characters of the
candidates and
their politics.

33:38.549 --> 33:40.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So they try to argue, it's not a
referendum.

33:40.618 --> 33:45.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you see thousands and
thousands of dollars
coming from small donors out of
state to Quist

33:45.223 --> 33:49.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in some support for him, maybe
the last stand
or the stand they're trying to
make in Montana

33:49.961 --> 33:52.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to say, we aren't happy with the
Trump -- with
what the Trump administration is
doing.

33:52.997 --> 33:56.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think, to a certain
extent, you have
to argue that Trump, the Trump
administration

33:56.134 --> 34:00.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and what has been coming out has
had an impact
on the race and certainly on
fund-raising

34:00.471 --> 34:01.973 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for Quist.

34:02.006 --> 34:04.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it will be interesting to
see how much
impact it has tomorrow night.

34:04.442 --> 34:08.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Anna Rau of
Montana PBS, thank
you very much.

34:08.246 --> 34:11.582 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANNA RAU: Yes, thank you.

34:11.616 --> 34:22.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: big changes
at the EPA
in the Trump administration.

34:22.527 --> 34:27.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As a candidate, the president
vowed to get
rid of it in -- quote -- "almost
any form."

34:27.565 --> 34:32.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The budget he unveiled yesterday
would reduce
its budget by a third, more than
any other

34:32.470 --> 34:34.272 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
federal agency.

34:34.305 --> 34:39.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is less known is a series
of recent moves
that would give industry more of
a voice when

34:39.577 --> 34:43.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it comes to shaping its approach
to scientific
recommendations.

34:43.181 --> 34:46.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's the focus of our Leading
Edge segment
tonight.

34:46.984 --> 34:48.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown looks at what's
afoot.

34:48.886 --> 34:53.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It all has to do
the way the
EPA and the government evaluate
science underlying

34:53.658 --> 34:55.393 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
many regulations.

34:55.426 --> 34:59.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Earlier this month, the EPA and
the Interior
Department announced they would
review and

34:59.263 --> 35:03.401 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
overhaul who serves on key
scientific advisory
boards.

35:03.434 --> 35:08.739 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The EPA move attracted
particular notice,
since its administrator, Scott
Pruitt, decided

35:08.773 --> 35:14.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not to renew the contracts for
half the members
of the so-called Board of
Scientific Counselors.

35:14.545 --> 35:19.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our scientific correspondent,
Miles O'Brien,
is here now to help fill in the
picture.

35:19.150 --> 35:23.588 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So, Miles, the Board of
Scientific Counselors,
what is that?

35:23.621 --> 35:25.323 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What do they do?

35:25.356 --> 35:31.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Jeff, a formerly
obscure board
at the EPA made up of 18
scientists, most

35:31.496 --> 35:37.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of them academics, a few of them
from industry,
their goal is to get really deep
in the weeds

35:37.068 --> 35:43.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with EPA staff researchers and
give them some
sound advice on research
priorities and equipment

35:43.741 --> 35:47.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and techniques that allow them
to do their
work.

35:47.211 --> 35:49.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They do not get involved in
policy, however.

35:49.280 --> 35:51.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What exactly
happened last
week?

35:51.516 --> 35:56.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, nine of
them whose term
had come up, their first term
came up, were

35:57.021 --> 36:02.059 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
told they were not being
automatically renewed,
which has been the practice in
the past.

36:02.093 --> 36:04.061 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It is an unusual move.

36:04.095 --> 36:09.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They were told they could
reapply for their
jobs, but it is something that
has taken that

36:09.934 --> 36:12.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
board aback, for sure.

36:12.203 --> 36:17.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I spoke with the chairperson of
the Board
of Scientific Counselors,
Deborah Swackhamer.

36:17.542 --> 36:20.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's a professor emerita at the
University
of Minnesota.

36:20.878 --> 36:22.680 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She was quite shocked.

36:22.713 --> 36:24.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DEBORAH SWACKHAMER, Chair, Board
of Scientific
Counselors: It is highly unusual
for someone

36:24.148 --> 36:25.816 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to not be reappointed.

36:25.850 --> 36:31.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is not a political board in
any way,
shape or form, and we don't
advocate for any

36:31.856 --> 36:34.492 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
kind of regulation or lack of
regulation.

36:34.525 --> 36:36.227 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We're not political.

36:36.260 --> 36:41.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So to say that we are somehow --
we would
behave differently because we
were appointed

36:41.165 --> 36:45.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
under President Obama is --
actually, it's
a little insulting.

36:45.369 --> 36:46.771 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We are scientists.

36:46.804 --> 36:50.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are not going to be swayed by
who's president
or who is administrator.

36:50.308 --> 36:56.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have served under three
presidents and four
administrators of EPA in my time
on various

36:56.681 --> 37:00.885 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
boards, and it never has
influenced how I
think about the science that I'm
reviewing.

37:00.918 --> 37:06.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So, the board
stands by its
autonomy and its objectivity,
and yet this

37:06.791 --> 37:08.693 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
happens, Jeff.

37:08.726 --> 37:10.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so what was
the reason
-- the reasoning given by the
Trump administration?

37:10.595 --> 37:16.434 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, a
spokesperson for the
EPA says this: "We should have
people who

37:16.467 --> 37:21.138 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
understand the impact of
regulations on the
regulating community."

37:21.172 --> 37:26.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The administrator of the EPA,
Scott Pruitt,
last month was in Pennsylvania
talking to

37:26.077 --> 37:31.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some coal miners, and he was
talking about
the broader issue of industry
input on EPA

37:31.882 --> 37:32.850 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
regulations.

37:32.883 --> 37:34.819 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Listen to this.

37:34.852 --> 37:36.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT PRUITT, Environmental
Protection Agency
Administrator: As we spend time
with the industry

37:36.787 --> 37:39.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
across this country recognizing
that we have
such opportunity with respect to
energy independence,

37:39.557 --> 37:43.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that just by spending time, some
on those
on the environmental left think
that we're

37:43.694 --> 37:46.831 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
somehow compromising outcomes
with respect
to our environment.

37:46.864 --> 37:52.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so, Miles,
a new administration,
as you say, often get to appoint
a lot of

37:52.236 --> 37:53.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
their own new people.

37:53.871 --> 37:56.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What kind of responses were you
hearing about
this action?

37:56.841 --> 38:01.012 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, it's a
definite shift.

38:01.045 --> 38:04.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there is something at work
here that's
been going on for quite some
time.

38:04.882 --> 38:10.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I spoke to a former assistant
administrator
for the EPA during the George W.
Bush administration,

38:10.688 --> 38:11.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Holmstead.

38:11.722 --> 38:14.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's now an attorney in private
practice.

38:14.258 --> 38:19.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it is his contention -- and
this is widely
held in conservative circles --
that simply

38:19.964 --> 38:24.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stating a conflict of interests
is enough
to eliminate it.

38:24.268 --> 38:26.304 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is what he has to say.

38:26.337 --> 38:28.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY HOLMSTEAD, Former EPA
Assistant Administrator:
See, I don't understand why
there's a conflict.

38:28.072 --> 38:32.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As long as they are disclosed,
the fact that
someone has done some consulting
work for

38:32.543 --> 38:37.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
industry shouldn't disqualify
them from offering
their scientific views on
things.

38:37.915 --> 38:43.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those -- anyone who's
engaged in that
debate can take those views into
account.

38:43.454 --> 38:47.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And, of course,
on the other
hand, many in the science
committee fear a

38:48.025 --> 38:53.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
broader move towards greater
influence for
the industry, those who are
being regulated.

38:53.531 --> 38:55.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes.

38:55.232 --> 39:00.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The concern here, Jeff, is that
if you stack
these boards with people who are
industry

39:00.371 --> 39:05.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
researchers, who are weighing in
on subject
matters that affect the
corporations that

39:05.242 --> 39:09.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pay their salaries, that that is
going to
put the thumb on the scale or in
some way

39:09.914 --> 39:14.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
block regulation that would be
scientifically
justified.

39:14.251 --> 39:18.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a reasonable concern, and
we're kind
of in the middle of this debate
between traditional

39:18.856 --> 39:22.927 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
academics and industry
researchers to try
to sort this out.

39:22.960 --> 39:25.496 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, what is to
come?

39:25.529 --> 39:26.564 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What is next?

39:26.597 --> 39:28.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, this is
what's interesting.

39:28.399 --> 39:32.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are 21 separate boards of
all manner
that are advising the
Environmental Protection

39:32.803 --> 39:34.071 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Agency.

39:34.105 --> 39:37.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The granddaddy of them all is
the Scientific
Advisory Board.

39:37.541 --> 39:40.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Changing its constituency
requires a vote
of Congress.

39:40.344 --> 39:43.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so far, the House has done
just that.

39:43.114 --> 39:49.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In March, it passed legislation
which would
allow the EPA to change the
rules to allow

39:49.854 --> 39:53.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more industry input on that
Scientific Advisory
Board.

39:53.824 --> 39:58.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Couple that with the so-called
secret science
legislation which makes it very
difficult

39:58.496 --> 40:05.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for researchers on these boards
to use certain
types of data related to human
