50:33.263 --> 50:35.098 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Those words are?

50:35.132 --> 50:36.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KYLE DIXON: "Stranger Things."

50:36.566 --> 50:38.068 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

50:38.101 --> 50:39.569 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: "Stranger
Things," and everybody
kind of gets the sense of...

50:39.603 --> 50:40.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KYLE DIXON: Yes, you're like,
OK, OK.

50:40.704 --> 50:41.671 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I get it.

50:41.705 --> 50:43.473 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

50:43.507 --> 50:45.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the meantime, scientists and
engineers
keep coming up with new things
for musicians

50:45.876 --> 50:47.411 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to try.

50:47.444 --> 50:50.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dave Rossum designed some of the
modules,
or components, on this
synthesizer.

50:50.714 --> 50:54.418 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVE ROSSUM, Rossum
Electro-Music: These modules,
we call them universal control
voltage generators.

50:54.451 --> 50:59.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's a very big batch of
words, but, basically,
it just means that they're
creating interesting

50:59.289 --> 51:02.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
electronic signals, so that we
can make interesting
notes.

51:02.926 --> 51:13.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: At Moogfest, you
could build
your own synthesizer, at least a
simple model.

51:13.336 --> 51:18.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Comedian Hannibal Buress, who
performed at
the festival, decided he
couldn't miss this

51:18.075 --> 51:19.176 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
class.

51:19.209 --> 51:20.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HANNIBAL BURESS, Comedian: Got
to try to do
that.

51:20.577 --> 51:24.147 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's the most extreme thing
you could do.

51:24.181 --> 51:28.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For some of us, I
think that's
right.

51:28.118 --> 51:29.953 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, how's it going?

51:29.986 --> 51:33.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HANNIBAL BURESS: It was a little
tough getting
some of the components in
initially, but we

51:33.390 --> 51:36.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
figured it out, and now we're
midway through.

51:36.660 --> 51:39.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're in the soldering phase,
which is something
I have never done.

51:39.463 --> 51:40.864 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm not a crafty dude.

51:40.897 --> 51:43.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't work with my hands like
that.

51:43.166 --> 51:44.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I can't build a shelf.

51:44.668 --> 51:47.971 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Or I haven't done anything like
it before,
so I'm enjoying the experience.

51:48.004 --> 51:53.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A view of the
future was also
on display here, including a
demonstration

51:53.910 --> 51:58.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of so-called machine learning to
create new
music.

51:58.448 --> 52:02.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Google's Adam Roberts and Jesse
Engel showed
us A.I.

52:02.052 --> 52:10.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jam session, an artificial
intelligence program
that responds to the notes you
play with something

52:10.093 --> 52:18.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of its own creation, based on
input and analysis
of tens of thousands of existing
melodies.

52:18.602 --> 52:21.571 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is it now composing this music?

52:21.605 --> 52:22.606 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ADAM ROBERTS, Google: yes.

52:22.639 --> 52:23.607 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: yes?

52:23.640 --> 52:24.875 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ADAM ROBERTS: Yes, and so...

52:24.908 --> 52:26.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Based on all the
information
you have fed it?

52:26.943 --> 52:31.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM ROBERTS: There still was a
human incredibly
involved in creating that
system, deciding

52:31.581 --> 52:33.350 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what data to train it on.

52:33.383 --> 52:36.653 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Another
experiment, called
NSynth, is developed through a
huge database

52:36.686 --> 52:42.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of sounds of instruments and
more, including
animals, that form a so-called
neural net.

52:42.959 --> 52:51.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It allows merging two sounds to
create a new
one, even a trombone and a dog.

52:51.568 --> 52:57.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JESSE ENGEL, Google: We're just
creating the
ability to explore and express
ourselves in

52:57.507 --> 52:59.142 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
new ways using technology.

52:59.176 --> 53:00.343 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're not just creating tools.

53:00.377 --> 53:03.547 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're creating ways to make new
tools as well.

53:03.580 --> 53:07.450 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Technology at the
service of
music and art.

53:07.484 --> 53:19.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Jeffrey Brown
at Moogfest in Durham, North
Carolina.

53:19.262 --> 53:26.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Before we go
tonight, we want
take this moment to remember a
pioneer of

53:26.770 --> 53:30.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
public broadcasting and a
beloved member of
the "NewsHour" family.

53:31.007 --> 53:35.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Al Vecchione was the first
executive producer
of "The MacNeil/Lehrer Report."

53:35.912 --> 53:38.114 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He died today at the age of 86.

53:38.148 --> 53:44.054 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Al began his broadcasting career
at NBC, covering
stories around the world.

53:44.087 --> 53:50.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In addition to helping to launch
our original
program in 1975, Al became the
executive in

53:50.293 --> 53:57.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
charge of expanding from 30
minutes to creating
the nation's first hour-long
evening broadcast.

53:57.467 --> 54:01.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are so grateful for his
decades of work
and friendship.

54:01.238 --> 54:05.075 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We will miss you, Al.

54:05.108 --> 54:06.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's the "NewsHour" for
tonight.

54:06.643 --> 54:07.777 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm Judy Woodruff.

54:07.811 --> 54:10.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Join us online and again right
here tomorrow
evening.

